column168: On March 7, 2024, one (1) defective 275-gallon tote of UN1760 leaked approximately one (1) gallon of product to the trailer interior during transit. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted site. Crews deployed granular absorbents to the release and worked them in with hand tools. A forklift was utilized to perform a gravity transfer of the remaining product from the damaged 275-gallon tote into one (1) new 275-gallon tote. Additional granular absorbents were deployed to the trailer floor to remove any remaining material and worked in with hand tools.  All UN1760-impacted materials were collected and containerized into one (1) 35-gallon drum for disposal.

XPO Logistics terminal XCN experienced a UN2522 Visiomer Madame release from a 55-gallon metal drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 12-ounces of product released to a 2’ x 6” area of the metal drum lid/body. The release was due to the drum having the incorrect bung cap placed on it. The bung was replaced with a new one and secured for shipment on. The impacted drums were wiped down with absorbent pads which were then containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: Hepaco was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted the 150-gallon poly tote and the contractor was unable to determine the volume of material released due to a forklift puncture of one (1) 150-gallon poly tote. Hepaco personnel stated that they believed that some of the released material evaporated. Hepaco personnel transferred the remaining material into a new poly tote and generated one (1) 55-gallon poly drum containing the cut-up poly tote, impacted absorbents and PPE. The generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal in a secure location prior to the contractor demobilization. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Lone Star Hazmat (LSH) to remediate the impacted site. LSH repalletized the undamaged freight for continued shipping.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XDM experienced a UN3082 Mesotrione 40% SC release from a 135-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-gallons of product released to a 10’ x 15’ area of the concrete dock floor due to a puncture caused by other freight during dock operations. The material was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one for shipment on. Absorbents were then deployed and worked into the impacted area. The damaged tote was cut up and containerized along with all impacted absorbents, pads, and PPE into (4) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: SequenceEvent: When the contents were discovered being coded for a refusal at the station for being damaged, we discovered that the contents (Which were 2 2.5-gallon jugs of liquid machine detergent which was a hazmat under UN 1760 Corrosive liquids N.O.S. Technical name Sodium Hydroxide) have leaked a small amount of the contents out of the package. Some of the box is wet due on the exterior but that is rain that has soaked a portion of the packaging. Upon closure inspection the caps were loose, and the corrosive liquids were observed to originate at the affected area. None of the liquid contents from inside of the package has been released out of the box, but still leaked from the inner jugs. No inner packing was found inside of the package. DescribePack: The Jugs were observed to have no leaks upon discovery, but some of the liquid inside of the container was out of the container and was at the time of discovery staining the inner exterior box. The caps enclosing the jugs containing the corrosive solution were observed to be loose with the most recently escaped liquid appearing right below the cap. The caps on the containers were promptly tightened and no leaks were observed after test and observing for a leak. DurationRel: 3 and MitigateEffect: Upon awareness of the damaged hazmat, the caps were tightened prevent any further leaks.

R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Hull's Environmental Services, Inc. (HES) to remediate the impacted site. HES personnel overpacked the damaged 55-gallon drum in one (1) 85-gallon drum. The crew then deployed absorbents to the release and worked them in with hand tools. All impacted absorbents were containerized in one (1) 55-gallon drum. Both drums were staged onsite for disposal.

On March 6, 2024, one (1) 55-gallon drum of corrosive liquid was damaged by a faulty skid and released approximately one (1) quart of product to the dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Indiana Spill Response (ISR) to remediate the impacted site. ISR personnel placed the damaged 55-gallon drum into one (1) 95-gallon overpack that was labeled as salvaged material for further handling by R+L. Crews swept in soda ash, then collected the neutralized product with hand tools. ISR personnel wiped down the dock floor with absorbent pads and cleaners. One (1) 55-gallon drum of neutralized product, PPE, and any cleanup debris was staged onsite for disposal.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal LTU experienced a battery acid release from a 1750-pound UN2794 battery. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 20-gallons of product released to a 10’ x 20’ area of the wooden trailer floor due to improper loading/pallet failure. Absorbents and soda ash were deployed to clean and neutralize the impacted area. The battery was up righted and re-secured for shipment on. All impacted absorbents, pallet wood, and PPE were containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: Car was observed during a shove to the hump with ice on the protective housing and vapor visible.  Upon inspection, the A end liquid valve was encapsulated in ice and the plug was laying on the pressure plate unsecured and the valve was partially open.  The valve was closed, and the odor dissipated.  The ice was melted with water, the valve inspected, and no issue found.  The plug was properly secured and after a few minutes the valve was checked with snoop and no issues or releases were found.  No other issues were found, and the housing was secured with a seal and released back into transportation.

column168: EMPLOYEE CAME IN THE TRAILER TO LOAD PACKAGES AND SAW DISTRESSED HAZMAT PACKAGE ON TRAILER FLOOR IN UPRIGHT POSITION. HE LEFT NOTIFYING HIS SUPERVISOR. CAME TO RESPOND. SHE HAD HER PPE ON. SHE NOTIFIED THE SUPERVISOR THAT IT WAS A LEAKING HAZMAT AND VERBALLY THE AREA WAS CORDONED OFF. SHE FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET ADDING SILVERSHIELD LINERS UNDER HER NITRILE GLOVES. SHE CONTAINERIZED THE BOX IN SPILL TUB. SHE PH TESTED THE FLOOR AS THERE WERE MULTIPLE STAINS ON FLOOR. THE PH WAS 9. SHE USED WATER AND A PAPER TOWEL TO NEUTRALIZE PH TO 7. SHE WIPED AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE. BECAUSE OF LENGTH OF STAINS, SHE CHECKED THE ROLLERS AND PACKAGES. ALL ROLLERS AND PACKAGES WERE CLEAN. DUE TO DAMPNESS AND TIME, SHE OBTAINED A CORRUGATED PIECE OF CARDBOARD TO COVER ENTIRE ALL STAINS ON THE FLOOR. SHE BROUGHT THE PACKAGE TO THE PACKAGE SERVICE CENTER AND FOLLOWED PROPER DMP PROCEDURE AND DISPOSITION OF PACKAGE.

Hazmat itself was placed in a hazardous materials tote lined with a bag and is on the corrosive pallet in the Haz cage. column168: Hepaco was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 5ft-by-5ft area of the terminal concrete floor and estimated that one-hundred and thirty (130) gallons of material was released due to forklift damaging one (1) 275-gallon poly tote. Hepaco personnel transferred the remaining product from the damaged tote along with rinse water that was used to neutralize two (2) 85-gallon metal drums that Dayton terminal personnel used to collect the leaking product in prior to the contractor’s arrival. The rinse water was offloaded into one (1) 275-gallon poly tote. Hepaco personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted flooring and collected the spent absorbents and containerized it along with impacted debris into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal in a secure location prior to the contractor demobilization. The generated waste will remain onsite for Dayton Freight’s contracted hazardous waste vendor to coordinate disposal.

XPO Logistics terminal XWK experienced a UN3266 Flash Clene 1414 release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2 cups of product released to 1' x 1' area on the trailer floor and a 1' x 4' area on the trailer wall due to a cracked tote corner. The material was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one. The impacted areas were then neutralized and cleaned with soda ash and absorbent pads. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized along with all cleanup debris into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: SequenceEvent: Leaking package discovered during sortation. Package placed in lined hazmat tote and sent to QA. DescribePack: Metal jerrican and metal bottle in zip-tied plastic bags inside corrugated carton with styrofoam peanut filler. Defective spout weld on jerrican allowed leakage which shriveled styrofoam peanut filler, soiled jerrican, and damaged carton. Carton still bears label from previous shipping under TRK # 789447976697, returned as improper hazmat for missing hazmat documents on 23 Jan 2024. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Package placed in lined hazmat tote and sent to QA.

Environmental Works was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 40ft-by-20ft area of the concrete terminal floor and estimated that one hundred and fifty (150) gallons of material was released due to forklift damaging one (1) poly tote. Environmental Works personnel deployed a neutralizer and then a granular absorbent to the impacted area. The remaining material was transferred to a new poly tote. The spent material was recovered and placed into three (3) 30-gallon poly drums, one (1) 55-gallon metal drum and one (1) 55-gallon poly drum along with the cut-up damaged poly tote. Environmental Works personnel then pressure washed the impacted area and collected the impacted water and containerized the recovered material into one (1) 330-gallon poly tote. The generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal in a secure location prior to the contractor demobilization. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.
